			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: highly indecisive- i need opinions.<a name="55415"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 6 04 9:32 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I had the same problem as you, all of my character slots on my selection screen are full on both of my accounts, I just like variety. I've been playing for over 4 years and I only have one toon at lvl 65, my cleric, of all things. My first toon was a druid but I just don't like downtime, I'm a very antsy person and I love to be busy. My honest suggestion to you if you've really tried all the classes, is to either give 2boxing a try, or go back ot the bard. I really only enjoyed my bard after playing a ton of other classes, I learned a lot about them and it made me a much better bard. I like necros and beastlords but I'm not a pet class type of guy, unless it's charming, which I find infinitely more exciting than permanant pet handling. 
<br />
   What lvl did you play all these toons to? It really does matter, since some classes don't start to shine until well into thier 40s or so, even later for some. I know since you only have bits of time to play, it might be tough to stick with once class, but get to at least lvl 55 with a toon before you write it off, you won't regret it. I have 6 toons over lvl 55 but only one at 65 and my bard is the closest behind that, he's going straight to 65 without a doubt. I'm also enjoying my monk immensly, but I usually 2box him with my shammy, this has come to be my favorite duo. 
<br />
2boxing suggestions:
<br />

<br />
-Monk and Shammy: Like I mentioned, a very fun combo. The shammy can stand to seriously beef up the monk and slow the mobs enough for the monk to tank without a problem, not to mention the benefits of the shammy pet and dots for overall dps.
<br />

<br />
-Necro and Shammy: Another awesome combo, but if you don't like juggling controls, you won't like this combo. A lot of kiting tactics and ping-ponging aggro is neccesary at higher lvls (51+) but it's a serious breeze mid lvls (high 30s-40s). 
<br />

<br />
-Chanty and Necro: Very very very strong combo IMHO. If you like charming and really living on the edge, this combo Rocks! This twosome's most obvious advantage is mana, they have lots of it. If you want a duo you can hotkey most of, this may not be for you.  
<br />

<br />
-Druid and Shammy: Also a very fun combo, using the druid as healer and the shammy pet to tank you can accomplish a lot. You can also use the druid to quad while the shammy pet nips the heels after aggro is established. 
<br />

<br />
-SK and Shammy: Can be very frustrating at lower lvls but once you break the 40s this pair can really rumble as long as you can manage mana pools and aren't in the habit of spamming spells. 
<br />

<br />
   There's more, I mean the combos are limitless but these are my favorite. I also like Beastlord and Cleric a lot, but I have only played that duo at high lvls (65) with my friend's account, my BL stopped at 38. 
<br />
   Try 2boxing if you like, or try the bard but I garuntee you asking here is going to get a lot of folks telling you to try bards! Sounds to me like you need more excitement, when was the last time you had to do a sketchy CR? When was the last time you died horribly? Do some fun stuff! Maybe it's not just the toons but the fact that you need some life breathed into your EQ happenings. Go risk life and limb, die horribly and learn something new in the process, one of my favorite old haunts to do this in is KC but I have a lot of fun in Jaggedpine too. Skyfire is another fun one that can turn on you pretty quick. Have you ever tried charming with a druid? It can be really really fun, interest in my druid died at 51 or so, then I got into charming and I was 56 in 3 days, now I still have an awesome time duoing with my cleric and my druid in places like Nightmare and Disease, or Western Wastes even.
<br />
   You could also try joining a new guild, or finding a really good partner to raise h*ll with. My EQ days were seriously spiced up when I met one of my best EQ friends while I was kiting in the Dreadlands one day (a shammy), we've died so many times attempting the impossible, I always have so much fun and it's always good to have a partner in crime that's as willing to die as I am 
<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-13.gif" border="0" alt="LOL" hspace="2" /> :lol
<br />
When we get bored we do the caller cycle or make huge trains in PoD and see if we can take them all down using a combination of aggro kiting and swarming. You can do a lot more with 2 people and if you really find someone cool to hit it off with, it's that much better. 
<br />

<br />
So I guess I'm saying you should try more things and meet people at least a little bit. I was (still am) just like you in the fact that I usually only have snippetts of time and am not really much of a social butterfly, just be open to the people you meet and try not to exclude any idea from the realm of being fun or entertaining, in EQ you just never know. 
<br />
 <img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-1.gif" border="0" alt="Smiley" hspace="2" /> </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
